Master Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
OOP helps in writing structured and reusable code.

âœ… Core OOP Concepts:
ğŸ”¹ Class & Object â€“ A blueprint and its instance.
ğŸ”¹ Encapsulation â€“ Restricting access to data.
ğŸ”¹ Inheritance â€“ Reusing parent class properties.
ğŸ”¹ Polymorphism â€“ Using a function in different ways.

EXAMPLE CODE FOR BASIC UNDERSTANDING:
     using System;  // âœ… Imports the System namespace (needed for Console.WriteLine)

class Car  // âœ… Class Declaration: Defines a blueprint for creating Car objects
{
    public string brand;  // âœ… Property: A variable inside the class to store car brand

    public void Honk()  // âœ… Method: A function inside the class that performs an action
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Beep Beep!");  // âœ… Prints "Beep Beep!" when Honk() is called
    }
}

class Program  // âœ… Another class: The entry point of the program
{
    static void Main()  // âœ… Main Method: The starting point of execution
    {
        Car myCar = new Car();  // âœ… Object Creation: Creates a new Car object in memory

        myCar.brand = "Toyota";  // âœ… Assigns the value "Toyota" to the brand property of myCar

        Console.WriteLine(myCar.brand);  // âœ… Outputs the brand name (Toyota) to the console

        myCar.Honk();  // âœ… Calls the Honk() method of the myCar object, printing "Beep Beep!"
    }
}
